  "recommendation": "Avoid enflurane and all halogenated volatile anesthetic agents. The patient's CACNA1S 'Uncertain Susceptibility' result indicates an identified variant whose pathogenic significance cannot be confirmed or excluded, and RYR1 yielded no result (inconclusive). Malignant hyperthermia (MH) triggered by volatile anesthetics such as enflurane is potentially fatal, and neither gene result can rule out susceptibility. Use a non-triggering anesthetic technique (e.g., total intravenous anesthesia with propofol). If volatile anesthesia is unavoidable, ensure dantrolene is immediately available, have MH monitoring protocols in place, and arrange post-operative observation. Referral for in vitro contracture testing (IVCT) and/or more comprehensive genetic evaluation should be considered to clarify susceptibility status.",
  "classification": "Moderate",
  "implication": "CACNA1S encodes the alpha-1 subunit of the skeletal muscle dihydropyridine receptor (DHPR/CaV1.1), which interacts directly with RYR1 at the triadic junction to regulate excitation-contraction coupling and SR calcium homeostasis. Pathogenic CACNA1S variants (R1086H and R174W) disrupt DHPR's normal negative allosteric suppression of RYR1, causing enhanced RYR1 calcium release sensitivity to volatile anesthetics such as enflurane, which can precipitate fulminant malignant hyperthermia. 'Uncertain Susceptibility' indicates a CACNA1S variant of uncertain clinical significance was detected; while CACNA1S mutations account for approximately 1% of MHS cases, the two characterized pathogenic variants both sensitize skeletal muscle to volatile anesthetic triggers through distinct calcium dysregulation mechanisms. RYR1 'No Result' does not exclude MH susceptibility, as identifiable RYR1 mutations are found in only ~60% of confirmed MHS families. Together, these inconclusive results preclude confidently classifying the patient as MH-normal."
}
